===Verb===
{{en-verb|recasts|recasting|recast}}

# To [[cast]] or [[throw]] again.
#* {{RQ:Florio Montaigne Essayes|chapter=47|book=I|passage=the Roman gentlemen armed at all assayes, in the middest of their running-race, would cast and '''recast''' themselves from one to another horse.}}
# To [[mould]] [[again]].
#: {{ux|en|The whole bell had to be '''recast''' although it had only one tiny, hardly visible crack.}}
# To reproduce in a new [[form]].
#* '''1999''', Joyce Crick, translating Sigmund Freud, ''The Interpretation of Dreams'', Oxford 2008, p.33:
#*: Our conception of the world rises in us as our intellect '''recasts''' {{transterm|de|umgiesst}} the impressions it receives from without into the forms of time, space, and causality.
# {{lb|en|transitive|film|theatre}} To assign (roles in a [[play]] or [[performance]]) to different [[actor]]s.
#* '''2002''', Robert C. Allen, ''To Be Continued...: Soap Operas Around the World'', Routledge {{ISBN|9781134837038}}, page 153
#*: According to As the World Turns producer, Michael Laibson, the decision was made to '''recast''' the role, because the producers and writers felt it would annoy the audience to have Betsy discontinued so soon after her long-delayed marriage {{...}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|film|theatre}} To assign (actors) to different roles.
#: {{ux|en|She was '''recast''' as the villain.}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act or process of recasting.
# {{lb|en|linguistics}} An [[utterance]] translated into another [[grammatical]] form.
#: {{ux|en|Adults may use '''recasts''' to suggest corrections to mistakes in children's speech.}}

